BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Watering Hole Seminar Series: Dr. Alessandro Rotta Loria
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260407T213000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260407T230000Z
UID:e5d3584ba54c72297c6c71a93da60d1d@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Join us for this month’s Watering Hole! Dr. Alessandro Rotta
  Loria will present “Underground Climate Change: Threat and Resource for
  Urban Areas Worldwide.” In this talk\, Dr. Rotta Loria will explore how
  rising subsurface temperatures beneath cities are creating real challenge
 s for civil infrastructure\, public health\, and the environment\, while a
 lso highlighting how the urban underground could become a valuable\, untap
 ped source of heat that can be harnessed to power our cities.\n\nEach mont
 h\, we invite water experts to share their innovative work in a concise 15
 -minute presentation\, followed by refreshing networking opportunities wit
 h snacks and drinks. These gatherings are designed to create meaningful co
 nnections within our water community while providing insights into cutting
 -edge research and initiatives. Open to all students\, faculty\, and inter
 ested community members\, our Watering Holes offer a perfect blend of educ
 ation and social interaction in a welcoming environment.
LOCATION:O. T. Hogan Biological Sciences Building\, 2205 Tech Drive\, Evan
 ston\, IL
URL:https://sites.northwestern.edu/watercenter/1496-2/
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Daniel Tucker\, "A Reflection on the Eco Social Salon\, Site Seein
 g and Screening Series"
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260407T220000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T000000Z
UID:3309f8e53f455d41fdba951c4d5d9fe2@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:We are lining up a few Art\, Community and Environment worksho
 p events in spring quarter\, the first of which is Tuesday April 7th\, 5-7
 pm in the Kaplan Seminar Room (Kresge 2351)\, where we'll be hosting Danie
 l Tucker's talk "A Reflection on the Eco Social Salon\, Site Seeing and Sc
 reening Series."\nIf you are interested in attending\, please RSVP by Apri
 l 2nd via email to .\nECO SOCIAL SALON\, SITE SEEING AND SCREENING SERIES 
 is an event series and learning community that has convened irregularly in
  Philadelphia since 2023. The series focus is on presenting ecologically-t
 hemed artwork and taking collaborative excursions throughout the region. T
 he project was developed in response to an increased interest in infrastru
 ctural and bioregional practices that can visualize and embody the territo
 rial scale of both problems and solutions related to the climate crisis.\n
 DANIEL TUCKER makes documentaries\, publications\, classes\, exhibitions a
 nd events. His writings and lectures on the intersections of art and polit
 ics and his collaborative art projects have been published and presented w
 idely. His latest co-authored book “Lastgaspism: Art and Survival in the
  Age of Pandemic” (Soberscove\, 2022) was picked as a “Best Art Book o
 f 2022” by Hyperallergic. He has led graduate programs in museum studies
  and socially-engaged art for the last decade and is the Research Network 
 Chair of the international Arts in Society Research Network. He is current
 ly a fellow with the Center for Experimental Ethnography at the University
  of Pennsylvania and the Engaged Humanities Studio at Swarthmore College. 
 He recently developed the Curating Engagement Retreat with support of Wagn
 er Foundation and Public Trust\, and since 2023 he has organized the ongoi
 ng Eco Social Salon\, Site Seeing and Screening Series in Philadelphia.  
 \nART\, COMMUNITY\, AND ENVIRONMENT is a Kaplan Research Workshop Co-conve
 ned by Rebecca Zorach\, Department of Art History\, and Hollyamber Kennedy
 \, Department of Art History. Greg Ruffing is the Graduate Student Assista
 nt. This research workshop brings together faculty and graduate students i
 nterested in the intersections among art and architectural practice\, envi
 ronmental studies\, and communities. We seek to broaden definitions of kno
 wledge production beyond the academic to include Indigenous and opposition
 al knowledge\, collaborative practice\, reparative design\, and activist r
 esearch. We hope to learn from both historical studies and from current\, 
 “front-line” experiences\, asking how they create democratic and non-h
 ierarchical knowledge communities\, and what potential for social\, artist
 ic\, and environmental efficacy they possess.
LOCATION:Kresge Hall\, 1880 Campus Drive\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/640701
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Amanda Majeski Vocal Master Class
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T000000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T020000Z
UID:303abbc1bc9734158f815dd2f7e43d6f@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Part of the Tichio-Finnie Vocal Master Class Series \nLurdes 
 Zapata and Maya Behiri\, soprano\; Isabel Yang\, mezzo-soprano\; Leonardo 
 Mangalindan\, tenor\; Alan Darling\, piano \n\nThe Financial Times remark
 ed that soprano Amanda Majeski’s (‘06) “well-rounded soprano... is s
 o warm and glorious\, the singing so outstanding\, that she leaves no emot
 ions unstirred.” A celebrated interpreter of Mozart\, Strauss\, Wagner\,
  and Handel\, Majeski is acclaimed for her portrayal of the title role in 
 Janáček’s Káťa Kabanová\, which she debuted at the Royal Opera Hous
 e\, Covent Garden in 2019. Prior to that performance\, she made her Metrop
 olitan Opera debut as Countess Almaviva in a 2014 production of Le nozze d
 i Figaro and reprised the role for her mainstage debut at the Lyric Opera 
 of Chicago on just a few hours’ notice. Her 2025-26 season began with he
 r debut in the title role of Shostakovich’s Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk at t
 he BBC Proms and includes a return to Oper Frankfurt as Marta in The Passe
 nger\, as well as appearances as the Marschallin in Der Rosenkavalier with
  New Orleans Opera and engagements with the Rundfunk-Sinfonieorchester Ber
 lin for Szymanowski’s Stabat Mater and Mahler’s Fourth Symphony. In th
 is master class\, she coaches accomplished Bienen School voice and opera s
 tudents. \nW. A. Mozart\, “E Susanna non vien... Dove sono...” from L
 e nozze di Figaro \nMaya Behiri\, soprano \n\nCharles Gounod\, “Que fa
 is-tu\, blanche tourterelle” from Roméo et Juliette \nIsabel Yang\, me
 zzo-soprano \n\nGiacomo Puccini\, “Che gelida manina” from La bohème
  \nLeonardo Mangalindan\, tenor \n\nGiacomo Puccini\, “Quando m’en v
 o” from La bohème \nLurdes Zapata\, soprano
LOCATION:Patrick G. and Shirley W. Ryan Center for the Musical Arts\, 70 A
 rts Circle\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://www.music.northwestern.edu/events/amanda-majeski-vocal-master-
 class-0?eventdate=1775606400
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Strategic Storytelling: Nonfiction & Narrative | Sexual Assault Ac
 tion Month
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T000000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T013000Z
UID:d02d5bbccdb8647f530e44bab2dac388@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:For many survivors of interpersonal violence\, telling their s
 tory can be a crucial part of the healing journey. Being honest and vulner
 able in nonfiction writing can be a powerful experience\, but it can prese
 nt its own set of challenges\, especially if that writing is shared with t
 he world. This workshop will explore the many avenues that survivors may c
 hoose to explore their experiences through narrative nonfiction writing\, 
 offer prompts for reflection and self-compassion when sharing stories of h
 arm\, discuss how survivors can maintain their safety and well-being when 
 sharing their stories\, and hold space for free writing.  \n4/7 7:00pm Wo
 men’s Center  | Food provided | RSVP Required
LOCATION:Women's Center\, 2000 Sheridan Rd.\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/639971
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
