BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Tourmaline: Legacies of Living Free. The 40th Anniversary Keynote 
 Address for the Women's Center
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T213000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T230000Z
UID:b4bc3f90eb1723f709269cac3df6bfc1@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Best selling author and activist Tourmaline will speak via Web
 inar about her work on _Marsha: The Joy and Defiance of Marsha P. Johnson_
  and its connections to the theme we are using to describe forty years of 
 community\, education\, and advocacy at the Women's Center: Legacies of Li
 ving Free. \nWe will have time to enjoy Tourmaline in conversation with o
 ur own beloved Marquis Bey\, author of Black Trans Feminisms and take ques
 tions from our audience.\nThis event will be held via Zoom Webinar. It is 
 free and open to all. Please feel free to share with you networks and\, if
  you are in the Evanston or Chicago area\, see our website for information
  about acquiring a free copy of the book\, _Marsha: The Joy and Defiance o
 f Marsha P. Johnson_.
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/639907
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Antony Eastmond (The Courtauld Institute of Art\, University of Lo
 ndon): "Byzantium\, the Caucasus\, and Artistic Borders in the Medieval Wo
 rld"
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T220000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T233000Z
UID:9106a7d156d716eec4f3c02d5570f722@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:The Northwestern Medieval Colloquium and the Department of Art
  History are pleased to invite you to a talk by Professor Antony Eastmond 
 of the Courtauld Institute of Art\, University of London. \nAntony Eastmo
 nd (The Courtauld Institute of Art\, University of London): "Byzantium\, t
 he Caucasus\, and Artistic Borders in the Medieval World"\nThursday\, Apri
 l 16\, 2026\, 5 p.m.\, University Hall 201 (Hagstrum Room)\nThis lecture w
 ill consider some of the issues raised by trying to write a ‘national’
  history of art in the twenty-first century. I will address the questions 
 I am facing as I try to write a history of the arts of Georgia in the Cauc
 asus. How do we define the borders and benefits of a ‘national’ art\, 
 particularly as art history takes an increasingly global and transnational
  turn? What value is there is defining an art by geography\, language\, re
 ligion and/or ethnicity? And how can we deal with the vague and porous bor
 ders that demarcate political\, cultural and religious space in the middle
  ages? I will evaluate the risks of my approach\, and try to defend my bel
 ief that it is possible to write a national art history without nationalis
 m.\n \nAntony Eastmond is AG Leventis Professor of Byzantine Art at The C
 ourtauld Institute of Art\, University of London. He is currently a Fellow
  in Byzantine Studies at Dumbarton Oaks\, Washington DC. He has worked ext
 ensively on the arts of Byzantium and the Caucasus\, and on the fuzzy fron
 tier between the Christian and Islamic worlds. Ironically\, his last book\
 , Tamta’s World (2017)\, argued against the delimiting of art history by
  borders of language\, ethnicity\, religion\, or geography.
LOCATION:University Hall\, 1897 Sheridan Road\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/640675
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Clean Living: Lessons from a Chemical War: A talk by Dr. Thuy Tu
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T220000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T230000Z
UID:64f93c78ceca6fec98427d3716f51d91@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:For decades\, the multi-billion dollar health and wellness ind
 ustry has touted the virtues of clean living. This lecture asks: What do w
 e mean by clean? How did those ideas shift in the aftermath of the Vietnam
  War and the U.S. military’s widespread use of chemical weapons? What le
 ssons about living clean can we gather from those who have survived mass c
 ontamination?\nThuy Linh Nguyen Tu is Professor of American Studies in the
  Department of Social and Analysis at NYU. She is the author or editor of 
 five books\, most recently\, Experiments in Skin: Race and Beauty in the S
 hadows of Vietnam (Duke UP\, 2021)\, which was honored with multiple award
 s\, including the R. R. Hawkins Award and a Victor Turner Prize. She was t
 he former faculty director of the NYU Prison Education Program's Research 
 Lab and recently the co-leader of the Mellon Sawyer Seminar on "Transpacif
 ic Thought and the Problem of Asia."
LOCATION:Crowe Hall\, 1860 Campus Drive\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/639984
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
