BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:I Was Here: 2026 Community Show
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260423T050000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260423T050000Z
UID:c88e4d640c27a8da1089bb6143dbd1f7@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Art has been used throughout human existence as a unifying for
 ce and a wordless language to represent our curiosities\, communities\, an
 d aspirations. However\, artistic spaces and practices have not always bee
 n inclusive or accessible to everyone. For this community show\, we invite
 d artists to consider how their perspectives could be integrated in order 
 to redefine art in spaces and to reclaim art practices\, identities\, and 
 cultures that have complex histories. Exhibited pieces explore how creativ
 ity can be used as a tool to navigate the world and take ownership of real
 ity. Through stepping outside of the traditions of academic art and taking
  notice of what is encountered in day-to-day life\, these artists expand w
 hat is defined as art.\nWork by the following 24 artists is included in th
 e show:\nGary S.Kristen NeveuPatty Marfise-PattAnna WagnerMarcus P.Mark Ji
 menezAnupriya NRichard GessertAnn KogenMartinez E-BClayton ShuttleworthJoh
 annah Tomita MartinChen YuChiaanakwadXuanyi ZhaoSara Peak ConveryDaniel Fe
 rnandezNehir UsluJoseph MoraSiwei Simon XuTone JacksonMaelea TanLillian Al
 iMarvin Veloso
LOCATION:Norris University Center\, 1999 Campus Drive\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://www.northwestern.edu/norris/arts/dittmar-gallery/upcoming-exhi
 bits.html
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Three Steps Forward\, Two Steps Back: The Continued Struggle to Tr
 eat Mental Illness in America
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260423T050000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260423T050000Z
UID:a4780e344d8f73ad6aaf025be492b6e2@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:On display in the Eckenhoff Reading Room: Like a path through 
 a maze\, medical and societal responses to mental illness in America have 
 seen shifts and turns of imperfect progress. This exhibit explores both so
 cietal and medical treatments of mental illness in the US from the 18th ce
 ntury to today. It highlights institutional confinement\, medical and phar
 maceutical treatments\, the development of child psychiatry\, and the shif
 t to police as mental illness first responders. Patterns of advancement an
 d retreat carry through each case\, showing the struggle to properly treat
  mental illness continues today. \n\nThis exhibit was created to compleme
 nt the National Library of Medicine’s traveling exhibit\, Care & Custody
 : Past Responses to Mental Health\, on display in the Galter Library atriu
 m February 9-March 21\, 2026. Details about that exhibit are available her
 e.
LOCATION:Ward Building\, 303 E. Chicago Avenue\, Chicago\, IL
URL:https://galter.northwestern.edu/exhibits/28
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
